\section{Tidal Heating of Moons}
\label{heat}

Moons caught in MMR will excite each other's eccentricity and/or inclination. This will allow for tidal dissipation within each moon, generating tidal heating of the moons. Assuming that tidal dissipation within the moons keeps their orbits nearly circular, the rate of change of the moons' orbital energy due to outward migration is given by equation \ref{edottide}. However, the net change in the moons' orbital energy is

text:
\begin{align}
\label{edotorb}
\dot{E}_{\rm orb} &= \dot{E}_{1,{\rm orb}} + \dot{E}_{2,{\rm orb}} \nonumber \\
&= -\frac{\dot{a}_1}{a_1} E_{1,{\rm orb}} - \frac{\dot{a}_2}{a_2} E_{2,{\rm orb}} \nonumber \\
&= -\frac{\dot{a}_1}{a_1} \big( E_{1,{\rm orb}} + E_{2,{\rm orb}} \big) \, .
\end{align}

\begin{equation}
\label{edotheat2}
\dot{E}_{\rm heat} = \Omega_1 \bigg[ \frac{1}{2} \frac{\dot{a}_1}{a_1} \big(J_1 + J_2\big) \bigg] + \frac{\dot{a}_1}{a_1} \big( E_{1,{\rm orb}} + E_{2,{\rm orb}} \big) \, .
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
\label{eheat}
\dot{E}_{\rm heat} = \frac{21}{2} \frac{k_1}{Q_1} \frac{G M_{\rm p}^2 R_{\rm p}^5}{a_1^6} \Omega_1 e_1^2 \, .
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
\label{eeq}
e^2_{\rm eq} = \frac{1}{7(j-1)} \frac{M_1 M_2}{M^2} \bigg(\frac{R_{\rm p}}{R_1}\bigg)^5 \frac{Q_1}{Q_{{\rm p},1}} \frac{k_{\rm p}}{k_1} \, ,
